\begin_body

\begin_layout Standard
Extending capillary pressure
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The capillary pressure relation for drainage reads
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p_{c}=p_{ce}\left(\frac{S_{w}-S_{wc}}{1-S_{wc}}\right)^{-1/\lambda},
\]

\end_inset

and the capillary pressure at zero water saturation is 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{c}^{0}$
\end_inset

, which is a large number, e.g., 10
\begin_inset Formula $^{9}$
\end_inset

 Pa.
 We draw a tangent from [
\begin_inset Formula $S_{w},p_{c}^{0}$
\end_inset

]=[0,
\begin_inset Formula $p_{c}^{0}$
\end_inset

] to the capillary pressure curve above which touches the curve at [
\begin_inset Formula $S_{w}^{*},p_{c}^{*}$
\end_inset

], i.e.,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{p_{c}^{*}-p_{c}^{0}}{S_{w}^{*}}=\frac{-1}{\lambda}\frac{p_{ce}}{1-S_{w}^{c}}\left(\frac{S_{w}^{*}-S_{wc}}{1-S_{wc}}\right)^{-1/\lambda-1},
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p_{c}^{*}=p_{ce}\left(\frac{S_{w}^{*}-S_{wc}}{1-S_{wc}}\right)^{-1/\lambda}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let's approach the problem this way:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
ln\left(\frac{p_{c}}{p_{ce}}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_body
